04704nam a22005775i 9780226237329DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20152015ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2014033480  a9780226237329  a(DE-B1597)525038  a(OCoLC)910848005  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aHD45b.O7294 2015 4aHD45b.O7294 2016 7aBUS0000002bisacsh04a658.575223  aQC 3442rvk1 aOreg, Shaul, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aResistance to Innovation :bIts Sources and Manifestations /cJacob Goldenberg, Shaul Oreg. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (208 p.) :b18 halftones, 13 line drawings, 23 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tPart I: Sources of Resistance -- tChapter 1. It’s Not the Innovation, It’s the Adopter: Why Some People Are More Likely Than Others to Resist -- tChapter 2. What’s in It for Me, and What Do I Have to Lose? Practical Reasons for Resisting Innovation -- tChapter 3. It’s Not What You Introduce, It’s How You Do It: The Process of Innovation Introduction -- tChapter 4. Where and When Is the Innovation Introduced? The Role of Innovation Context in the Emergence of Resistance -- tPart II: Resistance Manifestations -- tChapter 5. Lagging: Innovation in Disguise -- tChapter 6. Resistance and the Dangers of Negative Word of Mouth -- tChapter 7. The Dual-Market Effect -- tEpilogue -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEvery year, about 25,000 new products are introduced in the United States. Most of these products fail—at considerable expense to the companies that produce them. Such failures are typically thought to result from consumers’ resistance to innovation, but marketers have tended to focus instead on consumers who show little resistance, despite these “early adopters” comprising only 20 percent of the consumer population. Shaul Oreg and Jacob Goldenberg bring the insights of marketing and organizational behavior to bear on the attitudes and behaviors of the remaining 80 percent who resist innovation. The authors identify two competing definitions of resistance: In marketing, resistance denotes a reluctance to adopt a worthy new product, or one that offers a clear benefit and carries little or no risk. In the field of organizational behavior, employees are defined as resistant if they are unwilling to implement changes regardless of the reasons behind their reluctance. Seeking to clarify the act of rejecting a new product from the reasons—rational or not—consumers may have for doing so, Oreg and Goldenberg propose a more coherent definition of resistance less encumbered by subjective, context-specific factors and personality traits. The application of this tighter definition makes it possible to disentangle resistance from its sources and ultimately offers a richer understanding of consumers’ underlying motivations. This important research is made clear through the use of many real-life examples.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aTechnological innovationsxPsychological aspects. 0aTechnological innovationsxSocial aspects. 70(DE-601)1061441030(DE-588)4059252-2aTechnischer Fortschritt2gnd 70(DE-601)2158187250(DE-588)4423936-1aInnovationsbereitschaft2gnd 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / General.2bisacsh1 aGoldenberg, Jacob, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z97831106904390 cprintz978022663260540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226237329423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226237329/original  a978-3-